Perthshire) or Whitestone (Birse, Aberdeenshire), but the surname may not have survived in Scotland. The placenames derive from Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>stān</i> ‘stone’ or their later Scots equivalents. Alternatively, a variant of   Whiston  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Whitston was born in 1471, in Whitstone, Cornwall, England. He married Joan Whetston in 1501, in Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1520, in his hometown, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1471–1520":"1471–1520","1475–1584":"1475–1584","1510–1569":"1510–1569","1569":"1569","1501":"1501","November 1510":"november 1510","1510":"1510","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1584":"1584","1471":"1471","Whitstone, Cornwall, , England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chesterton, Huntingdonshire, England":"Chesterton, Huntingdonshire, England","Whitstone, Cornwall, England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1471–1520":"1471–1520","1475–1584":"1475–1584","1510–1569":"1510–1569","1569":"1569","1501":"1501","November 1510":"marraskuu 1510","1510":"1510","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1584":"1584","1471":"1471","Whitstone, Cornwall, , England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Engla